      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm studying regularization for my ml class and im a bit stuck. can u explain the main difference between L1 and L2 regularization in terms of how they actually affect the model coefficients? like why would i pick one over the other?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure, I'd be happy to help you with that! L1 and L2 regularization are both techniques to prevent overfitting in machine learning models, but they handle the coefficients differently. L1 regularization, also known as Lasso, adds a penalty equal to the absolute value of the magnitude of the coefficients. This can lead to some coefficients being exactly zero, effectively performing feature selection. On the other hand, L2 regularization, also known as Ridge, adds a penalty equal to the square of the magnitude of the coefficients, which tends to shrink the coefficients towards zero but rarely exactly zero. L2 regularization is generally more stable and works well when you have multicollinearity in your data. You might choose L1 when you want to reduce the number of features or when you have a high-dimensional dataset, while L2 is better when you want to keep all features but reduce their impact.",
      "source": "target",
