      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense, but i dont really get the \"why\" behind the math. like, why does the absolute value in L1 actually force things to zero, whereas the squared penalty in L2 just makes them really small? is there a way to visualize why l1 is so much more aggressive at cutting out features?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I see, you're looking for a deeper understanding of the mathematical reasoning behind L1 and L2 regularization. Let's dive in!\n\nL1 regularization adds a penalty equal to the absolute value of the coefficients, which means it penalizes the absolute size of the coefficients. This can lead to some coefficients being exactly zero, effectively performing feature selection. The reason behind this is that the L1 penalty creates a \"sharp\" or \"L\"-shaped objective function, which has corners at the origin. This means that there are multiple solutions to the optimization problem, and the solution with the smallest L1 norm (sum of absolute values of coefficients) is preferred. This is why L1 regularization can be more aggressive at cutting out features.\n\nOn the other hand, L2 regularization adds a penalty equal to the square of the coefficients, which means it penalizes the squared size of the coefficients. This creates a \"smooth\" or \"U\"-shaped objective function, which has a single minimum at the origin. This means that there is only one solution to the optimization problem, and the solution with the smallest L2 norm (sum of squared values of coefficients) is preferred. This is why L2 regularization tends to shrink the coefficients towards",
      "source": "target",
